Here's a typical `MauiProgram.cs` setup:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

namespace MyMauiApp;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder
            .UseMauiApp<App>()
            .ConfigureFonts(fonts =>
            {
                fonts.AddFont("OpenSans-Regular.ttf", "OpenSansRegular");
            });

        // Services
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

#if DEBUG
        builder.Logging.AddDebug();
#endif

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `DataService` | **Singleton** | Holds an `HttpClient` and shared state (cache, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps config consistent app-wide. |
| `MainViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation creates a fresh VM with clean state — no stale data leaking between visits. |
| `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Same reason — each detail screen gets its own instance so different items don't collide. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Matches the VMs. A new page + new VM per navigation avoids UI state bugs. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** → stateful services shared app-wide (HTTP clients, caches, settings).
- **Transient** → pages and ViewModels so each navigation gets a fresh instance.
- **Scoped** → rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET), but useful if you create your own scopes for multi-step workflows.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **transient** or **scoped** service into a **singleton** — the short-lived service would be captured and kept alive forever, defeating its lifetime. The DI container will throw at runtime if you enable scope validation.
